Key Command-Line Options
You use these when starting top from the terminal (e.g., top -b):

-b: Batch mode. Useful for sending output to other programs or files (it won't clear the screen or handle keyboard input).
-n <number>: Number of iterations. Tells top to update the screen X times and then exit.
-d <seconds>: Delay time. Sets the update interval (e.g., top -d 2).
-u <username>: Monitor processes owned by a specific user.
-p <PID>: Monitor only processes with the specified Process IDs.
-i: Starts top ignoring idle or zombie processes.


1. Monitoring a specific user
If you want to see only the processes owned by the user labex:

top -u labex
2. Batch mode (for logging to a file)
If you need to capture the state of your system to a file for later analysis, you can use batch mode. This will run 5 iterations and then save them to a file named sys_stats.txt:

top -b -n 5 > sys_stats.txt
After running this, you can check the file with cat sys_stats.txt.

3. Setting a custom refresh rate
By default, top updates every 3 seconds. If you want to see changes faster, for example, every 1 second:

top -d 1
4. Monitoring a specific process
If you want to watch the resource usage of a specific process (let’s say its PID is 36), use:

top -p 36
(You can find the PID of any process in the first column of the standard top display.)

5. Combining options
You can combine flags to get specific results. For example, to run top for a specific user, in batch mode, for exactly 3 iterations:

top -u labex -b -n 3
Pro-Tip: Interactive Examples
Remember, you don't always need flags! Once you run top (just type top), try these keys on your keyboard:

M (Shift + m): Sort processes by Memory usage.
P (Shift + p): Sort processes by CPU usage (the default).
c: Show the full command path instead of just the process name.
q: Quit top.
